thread.title: Defense rules as Falmouth, D-Y play to draw
thread.title_full: Defense rules as Falmouth, D-Y play to draw

author: Cape Cod Times sports@capecodonline.com
title: Defense rules as Falmouth, D-Y play to draw
text: Posted Oct. 10, 2015 at 9:33 PM By Cape Cod Times Posted Oct. 10, 2015 at 9:33 PM » Social News FALMOUTH - In a defensive battle that saw the host Clippers hold off a furious first-half push from the visiting Dolphins, Falmouth and Dennis-Yarmouth battled to a scoreless tie in the Atlantic Coast League field hockey contest on Saturday The Clippers (5-1-3, 3-1-1 ACL) were limited to just three shots on the D-Y cage over the entire game. Falmouth did not have a corner in the game. The Dolphins (5-3-1, 3-1-1 ACL) swarmed the Clipper end of the field especially in the first half. In the game, D-Y had 15 corners, but the Falmouth defense, anchored by goalie Molly Duff-Still as well as the back line of Hannah Callahan, Chloe Crago, Rachel Curtis and Kate Hamilton, managed to keep the visitors off the board. Duff-Still, a junior, recorded her fourth shutout of the season while making seven saves between the Clipper pipes. Next up for the Clippers is a Wednesday non-league match at home against arch-rival Barnstable while the Dolphins next take the field Monday on the road at Nantucket. Martha’s Vineyard 4, Nantucket 0: Lacey Dinning scored a pair of goals and older sister Belle added a goal in the Vineyarders shutout win over the Whalers in Oak Bluffs. Julia Bettencourt earned the shutout in goal for Martha’s Vineyard (6-2-1), which is three points away from a South Sectional qualifying berth after the victory. Juniper Ezanno scored just six minutes in as Belle Dinning doubled the lead merely four minutes later. Lee Hayman assisted both, sending in a beautiful corner to Dinning as the Vineyarders took a 2-0 advantage to the half. Lacey Dinning then scored her two goals, her first off an assist from sister Belle and her second on a pass from Ginny Kent. Martha’s Vineyard also got strong play on defense from Emma Caron and in the midfield from Kyle Hatt. Nantucket drops to 5-5. BOYS SOCCER Nantucket 1, Martha’s Vineyard 1: Miles Jordi equalized for the Vineyarders just before the half and the hosts held on for a non-league point against the Whalers in Oak Bluffs. Jordi finished off a pass from Jason Lages with roughly five minutes to go in the opening half, with neither side willing to relinquish the game-winner in the second half. Luiz Terragno gave Nantucket (7-0-1) a 1-0 lead just 15 minutes in, scoring on a Renaldo Powell pass, before Jordi’s goal tied things up later in the half. Martha’s Vineyard (6-3-1) got a strong team effort in the match, with key play in the midfield from Nevin Wallis. The Whalers got strong play on defense from Carter Snell and Gus Day and Simon Johnson while Andrew Dawson were key in the midfield. GIRLS SOCCER Nantucket 1, Martha’s Vineyard 0: Kate Daniels’ goal midway through the second half was all the Whalers would need to beat the Vineyarders on Nantucket. Daniels knocked home a Katherin Pitman assist in the middle of the second half to help the Whalers improve to 6-3. Martha’s Vineyard is 2-7-1. By Cape Cod Times
